text:
65 W. 39th Street, at the N. E. corner of Sixth Avenue, (general view north).

Three views in a northward direction up Sixth Avenue from the above location. Note the old "El" structure upon same with its 42nd Street station. This line was completely razed in May 1939. To the lower right is Bryant Park and its 42nd Street side. Times Square is to the left and its most prominent feature, the Paramount Building, appears in one of these views. Partially obscuring same is the cathedral type Bush Terminal Building (No. 130-2 W. 42nd Street). The 22 story Lewishon Building (No. 114 W. 41st Street thru to 113-119 W. 40th Street) is to the left and bears the Wurlitzer sign.

February 28, 1930
Views: 1, 2 and 3

text:
65 W. 39th Street, at the N. E. corner of Sixth Avenue, (general view northeastward).

Two views across the eastern end of Bryant Park and the rear of the New York Public Library towards the Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street intersection. To the left, on the latter thoroughfare is, a low building occupied by the Stern Brothers Department Store, the 18 story Aeolian Building and the mammoth Salmon Tower Building. To the right of the latter are, the Lefcourt National Building and the Grand Central Building.

text:
65 W. 39th Street, at the N. E. corner of Sixth Avenue, (general view northeastward).

A series of three similar views from the above location across Bryant Park and the New York Public Library to Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street intersection. The latter is plainly shown and predominates with the Salmon Tower Building (No. 11 W. 42nd Street). Adjoining same to the left is the 18 story Aeolian Building (No. 29-33 W.). To the right is the Lefcourt National Building, a structure that replaced the Temple Emanuel at the N. E. corner of Fifth Avenue and 43rd Street. This today would be obscured from this vantage point as the 500 Fifth Avenue Building was subsequently erected adjoining the Salmon Tower. Note the Grand Central Building in the background.

February 28, 1930

text:
65 W. 39th Street, at the N. E. corner of Sixth Avenue, (general view westward).

A set of two views towards and across Broadway at 39th Street, showing there an excavation for the 33 story Brickten-Casino Building (No. 1410 Broadway) and low structures opposite. Beyond the latter appear structures on Seventh Avenue, the three in the center being, the 43 story Navarre Building (No. 508 Seventh Avenue), the 22 story Fashion Center Building (rear view, No. 521 Seventh Avenue), and the 30 story structure, No. 528 Seventh Avenue. To the right foreground and with tower atop, is the 23 story, Lefcourt Manhattan Building (No. 1412 Broadway).

P. L. Sperr
